@Andrzej

At the schools I worked in, you'd be risking life and limb by calling the custodian a janitor.  Custodians, at least where I worked, were in charge of keeping the building in working order, which included all the mechanicals.  They had to be able to fix the furnace or do electrical work.  They may have rags in the supply closet, but they had underlings to clean the building.  

Yet even in that context, the people under the custodian, who I guess was actually was called the head custodian, were considered "custodians," not "janitors," and would take offense at the latter term.

@Andrzej
I'm curious: were  you familiar with the term LAUGH LINES for facial wrinkles? I pictured you and other foreign solvers stumbling on it.

As for rags... to me a rag is an old t-shirt or sock that's too worn to wear and is repurposed for cleaning. I tend to call store-bought ones cleaning cloths. Rags can also described tattered clothing, as in "The poor girl was dressed in rags".  And finally "rag" is a dismissive term for some newspapers deemed lesser. Pretty versatile word! ;)

